2. a. d. v, K., etc.: i.e. Nov. 26 under the old calendar, or Sept. 23 under the new. The Roman calendar was so far from correct at this time, that Jan. 1, 46 B.c.‚ came in the middle of the autumn. This state of things Caesar remedied by the in- sertion of 90 extra days into the year 46 B.c. The year 46 con- tained, therefore, 445 days. After the Terminalia (Feb. 23), an inter- calary month of 23 days was in- serted, and between November and December two intercalary months were inserted containing together 67 days.
